NEW BATTLEGROUNDS IN INFORMATION WARFARE [3]
INFORMATION CAMPAIGNS CAN BE AS BIG A THREAT TO NATIONAL SOVEREIGNTY AS MILITARY CAMPAIGNS.
BY: RONAN WORDSWORTH
The concept of disinformation isn’t new; it’s been around as long as information has. The difference between then and now is that now there are more, and arguably more effective, avenues for
controlling public opinion. And there are more people trying to control it. In addition to large media organizations, which can, to varying degrees, cooperate with the state, virtually anyone can try
to control information. As a result, trust in institutions has been eroded, democratic processes have been undermined, perceptions have been altered, and societies have been conditioned to be
disillusioned throughout the world. Governments have realized that information campaigns can be as big a threat to national sovereignty as military campaigns.
ADOPTION AND DEPLOYMENT
Foreign information manipulation and interference, or FIMI, has been recognized as a growing security threat. One small but significant component of FIMI is disinformation – that is, misleading
content that is meant to deceive. This is not to be confused with misinformation: information that is merely inaccurate. Both, however, can affect public health, subvert attempts to address certain
challenges, destabilize societies, shape narratives and undermine adversaries.
As the use of FIMI becomes more frequent, governments increasingly lack the tools to adequately counter it. It’s no easy task; education in, say, media literacy typically lags behind new forms of
FIMI. But the bottom line is that as the threat matrix grows, so do the risks of inaction. Russia was perhaps the earliest and most high-profile proponent of mass-scale disinformation operations, and
though they are especially useful to authoritarian regimes acting against democratic adversaries, countless state and non-state actors weaponize FIMI as a tool of asymmetric warfare.
There are many reasons for engaging in disinformation. One is to sow division and discord. When done properly, it is invaluable. It can turn citizens against each other, undermine trust in otherwise
trusted groups and institutions, influence the outcomes of elections and shape government policy. Another reason is to promote positive narratives for preferred figures. Russia frequently attempts to
undermine the credibility of pro-Europe leaders and promote pro-Russia ones.
In fact, Russia is a logical starting point in looking for examples of information warfare. Through coordinated operations by state and pro-Kremlin affiliates, Moscow was one of the earliest adopters
of social media for large-scale disinformation activities. Whether on Facebook, X/Twitter, WhatsApp or, now, video platforms like TikTok and Instagram Reels, disinformation campaigns have also become
increasingly sophisticated.
The strategy is as important as the message. Russia, for instance, has a tried and true method for waging information warfare. First, it creates a narrative or specific angle of attack. Rather than
being an outright lie, the message is usually based on a kernel of truth that taps into local grievances and thus appears legitimate. This can take the form of doctored images, memes, fabricated
statistics and completely misleading headlines. Once the content is created, the message is amplified by pushing the narrative, over and over, in a process called “flooding the zone.”
The narratives are often picked up by others, including state-controlled media accounts, troll farms, private entities' social media channels and paid local influencers. They are also spread liberally
across as many platforms as possible to help amplify the message and give it credibility. Meanwhile, the person or group that issued the disinformation often sends out competing narratives to
overwhelm its targets with content. This further obfuscates the truth by normalizing more “moderate” accounts of an otherwise extreme narrative. Crucially, support for these messages can develop
organically through local influencers who actually believe the false narrative. Multipronged strategies like these necessarily have a built-in layer of plausible deniability for whoever issued the
disinformation.
Other countries follow similar playbooks, of course, while some use their own. China, for example, tends to use disinformation as a piece in a larger campaign that includes cyber threats, intimidation
of critical voices with transnational repression and economic coercion – all in the service of pushing pro-Beijing narratives and silencing critics. Though it’s not as ubiquitous as Russia, China
has been ready to deploy voices when needed to change the narrative on particular topics, especially those around the COVID-19 pandemic and Taiwan.
GEOPOLITICAL CONSEQUENCES
The mass adoption of FIMI operations has a number of direct consequences, perhaps the most important of which is that it doesn’t require a ton of material capability to carry out. In more concrete
terms, however, Russian activity is instructive because it has been wildly successful and because it offers two helpful use cases: disrupting internal stability in the domestic markets of Western
countries and undermining the West as part of a broader competition for influence in the so-called Global South.
Indeed, Africa has become arguably one of the most frequent targets of FIMI operations [4] as many new actors emerge to compete for influence there, but Russia was sort of a pioneer in the modern
information warfare era. It started in the Central African Republic, then parlayed its successes over the past few years to the Sahel region, including Mali, Burkina Faso, Niger and beyond. Many of
these countries had legitimate grievances with their former colonial master, France. These grievances were amplified such that the population demanded that French troops leave. It culminated in the
ouster of democratically elected governments by military juntas, ostensibly for being too pro-France. Local influencers were paid directly by Russian agents to push Kremlin talking points. Local media
outlets were chosen to amplify the message and ensure the domination of Moscow’s narrative in the information sphere.
There are many benefits for Russia. In exchange for providing soldiers (and mercenaries through private outfits like Africa Corps) to embattled juntas, Russia received significant mining rights
throughout the region. Burkina Faso, despite claims of nationalizing gold mines operated by Canadian and Australian companies, has signed a new agreement with Russian miner Nordgold to extract gold
from a new mine in Niou. The site is expected to yield over 20 tons of gold over the next eight years to the tune of approximately $2.1 billion. The government will receive just $89 million. This deal
is being celebrated in Burkina Faso as a liberation from colonial powers, but it’s hard to argue that it’s any less exploitative.
Likewise, new Russian mining licenses are being granted in Mali and Niger, demonstrating the large return on investment achieved through FIMI. Along with the Central African Republic, the three
Sahelian states now have very popular public opinions of Russian intervention, even as internal security has weakened by every conceivable metric.
Notably, there are structural factors that make the Sahel especially vulnerable to Russian influence. They include low media and digital literacy in rural areas, insufficient traditional media
sources, a population only relatively recently introduced to the internet, the proliferation of chat groups on platforms like WhatsApp, a high level of trust in informal channels of media, and
distrust in institutions thanks to years of neglect by successive governments.
