Recent events in Romania are similarly illustrative. The presidential election last year featured a relative unknown outsider named Calin Georgescu, who rose to prominence and topped the polls in a
major surprise to observers and established parties alike. The constitutional court annulled the election results after intelligence documents revealed a targeted Russian influence operation was
promoting Georgescu. And it just so happened that he favored closer relations with Moscow than with Brussels.
Here again, Russia was able to effectively leverage an existing discontent with the status quo to promote an outsider who could have fundamentally altered Romania's democratic outlook. The campaign
was conducted via readily available media channels such as Instagram, TikTok and WhatsApp. In other words, Moscow was almost able to fundamentally change the direction of Romania’s foreign policy
using a relatively paltry amount of resources.
This case was the first time a Western country was forced to take concrete and drastic steps to counter FIMI operations. But in a democratic country, this has consequences of its own. The people who
voted for Georgescu believe democracy was undermined by the court’s nullification of the election results, while the people who voted against him also believed they were undermined. Governments that
follow the example of Bucharest risk pushing more people to extreme parties, especially if they believe mainstream parties are working against them. (It’s important to note, too, that no one likes
to admit that they were duped. This entrenchment adds another layer of complexity to an already difficult problem.)
NEW RISKS
Over the past two years, the risk posed by FIMI has been made worse by generative AI and automation. Generative AI allows users to produce images and videos that are nearly indistinguishable from
reality. Large language models allow external actors to produce convincing content in many languages without needing to expend the time and resources to groom local assets or learn the language
otherwise. Similarly, automation is a vital tool for amplifying messages hundreds of times to “flood the zone” with information. Whereas before troll farms required thousands of employees to
produce fake or doctored content, they can now be mass-produced and distributed with minimal labor across multiple platforms.
FIMI is a risk that evolves in lockstep with new technologies. That one country can affect another’s elections for its own geostrategic ends is fundamentally an act of aggression and undermines the
entire democratic process. The solutions required are complex and long-term. Russian Chief of General Staff Gen. Valery Gerasimov has said that the world is moving to a “nonlinear battlefield,”
where psychological, informational and cognitive operations are just as decisive to outcomes as kinetic operations. Vulnerable groups are manipulated for a host of reasons, and the cost of doing so is
significantly lower than a conventional challenge to the status quo.
On a state level, the European Union is a leader in countering FIMI. These operations require more than just fact-checking; once the disinformation is out there, the damage is often already done.
Effective counteroperations require investment in media literacy, regulatory frameworks for tech platforms to prevent rapid dissemination, and coordinated intelligence sharing among allies who
understand the risks.
