nd Deployment</strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Foreign informatio=
n manipulation and interference, or FIMI, has been recognized as a growing =
security threat. One small but significant component of FIMI is disinformat=
ion =E2=80=93 that is, misleading content that is meant to deceive. This is=
 not to be confused with misinformation: information that is merely inaccur=
ate. Both, however, can affect public health, subvert attempts to address c=
ertain challenges, destabilize societies, shape narratives and undermine ad=
versaries.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">As the use of FIMI=
 becomes more frequent, governments increasingly lack the tools to adequate=
ly counter it. It=E2=80=99s no easy task; education in, say, media literacy=
 typically lags behind new forms of FIMI. But the bottom line is that as th=
e threat matrix grows, so do the risks of inaction. Russia was perhaps the =
earliest and most high-profile proponent of mass-scale disinformation opera=
tions, and though they are especially useful to authoritarian regimes actin=
g against democratic adversaries, countless state and non-state actors weap=
onize FIMI as a tool of asymmetric warfare.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">There are many rea=
sons for engaging in disinformation. One is to sow division and discord. Wh=
en done properly, it is invaluable. It can turn citizens against each other=
, undermine trust in otherwise trusted groups and institutions, influence t=
he outcomes of elections and shape government policy. Another reason is to =
promote positive narratives for preferred figures. Russia frequently attemp=
ts to undermine the credibility of pro-Europe leaders and promote pro-Russi=
a ones.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">In fact, Russia is=
 a logical starting point in looking for examples of information warfare. T=
hrough coordinated operations by state and pro-Kremlin affiliates, Moscow w=
as one of the earliest adopters of social media for large-scale disinformat=
ion activities. Whether on Facebook, X/Twitter, WhatsApp or, now, video pla=
tforms like TikTok and Instagram Reels, disinformation campaigns have also =
become increasingly sophisticated.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The strategy is as=
 important as the message. Russia, for instance, has a tried and true metho=
d for waging information warfare. First, it creates a narrative or specific=
 angle of attack. Rather than being an outright lie, the message is usually=
 based on a kernel of truth that taps into local grievances and thus appear=
s legitimate. This can take the form of doctored images, memes, fabricated =
statistics and completely misleading headlines. Once the content is created=
, the message is amplified by pushing the narrative, over and over, in a pr=
ocess called =E2=80=9Cflooding the zone.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The narratives are=
 often picked up by others, including state-controlled media accounts, trol=
l farms, private entities' social media channels and paid local influencers=
. They are also spread liberally across as many platforms as possible to he=
lp amplify the message and give it credibility. Meanwhile, the person or gr=
oup that issued the disinformation often sends out competing narratives to =
overwhelm its targets with content. This further obfuscates the truth by no=
rmalizing more =E2=80=9Cmoderate=E2=80=9D accounts of an otherwise extreme =
narrative. Crucially, support for these messages can develop organically th=
rough local influencers who actually believe the false narrative. Multipron=
ged strategies like these necessarily have a built-in layer of plausible de=
niability for whoever issued the disinformation.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Other countries fo=
llow similar playbooks, of course, while some use their own. China, for exa=
mple, tends to use disinformation as a piece in a larger campaign that incl=
udes cyber threats, intimidation of critical voices with transnational repr=
ession and economic coercion =E2=80=93 all in the service of pushing pro-Be=
ijing narratives and silencing critics. Though it=E2=80=99s not as ubiquito=
us as Russia, China has been ready to deploy voices when needed to change t=
he narrative on particular topics, especially those around the COVID-19 pan=
demic and Taiwan.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>Geopolitic=
al Consequences</strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The mass adoption =
of FIMI operations has a number of direct consequences, perhaps the most im=
portant of which is that it doesn=E2=80=99t require a ton of material capab=
ility to carry out. In more concrete terms, however, Russian activity is in=
structive because it has been wildly successful and because it offers two h=
elpful use cases: disrupting internal stability in the domestic markets of =
Western countries and undermining the West as part of a broader competition=
 for influence in the so-called Global South.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Indeed,<a href=3D"=
https://geopoliticalfutures.com/mailster/401981/5e27030c0318f096cd26f3e94fd=
cf2a7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hZnJpY2FjZW50ZXIub3JnL3Nwb3RsaWdodC9tYXBwaW5nLWEtc3VyZ2Utb=
2YtZGlzaW5mb3JtYXRpb24taW4tYWZyaWNhLw" style=3D"color:#0e6ba5;text-decorati=
on:none;padding:2px 0px"> Africa has become arguably one of the most freque=
nt targets of FIMI operations</a> as many new actors emerge to compete for =
influence there, but Russia was sort of a pioneer in the modern information=
 warfare era. It started in the Central African Republic, then parlayed its=
 successes over the past few years to the Sahel region, including Mali, Bur=
kina Faso, Niger and beyond. Many of these countries had legitimate grievan=
ces with their former colonial master, France. These grievances were amplif=
ied such that the population demanded that French troops leave. It culminat=
ed in the ouster of democratically elected governments by military juntas, =
ostensibly for being too pro-France. Local influencers were paid directly b=
y Russian agents to push Kremlin talking points. Local media outlets were c=
hosen to amplify the message and ensure the domination of Moscow=E2=80=99s =
narrative in the information sphere.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">There are many ben=
efits for Russia. In exchange for providing soldiers (and mercenaries throu=
gh private outfits like Africa Corps) to embattled juntas, Russia received =
significant mining rights throughout the region. Burkina Faso, despite clai=
ms of nationalizing gold mines operated by Canadian and Australian companie=
s, has signed a new agreement with Russian miner Nordgold to extract gold f=
rom a new mine in Niou. The site is expected to yield over 20 tons of gold =
over the next eight years to the tune of approximately $2.1 billion. The go=
vernment will receive just $89 million. This deal is being celebrated in Bu=
rkina Faso as a liberation from colonial powers, but it=E2=80=99s hard to a=
rgue that it=E2=80=99s any less exploitative.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Likewise, new Russ=
ian mining licenses are being granted in Mali and Niger, demonstrating the =
large return on investment achieved through FIMI. Along with the Central Af=
rican Republic, the three Sahelian states now have very popular public opin=
ions of Russian intervention, even as internal security has weakened by eve=
ry conceivable metric.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Notably, there are=
 structural factors that make the Sahel especially vulnerable to Russian in=
fluence. They include low media and digital literacy in rural areas, insuff=
icient traditional media sources, a population only relatively recently int=
roduced to the internet, the proliferation of chat groups on platforms like=
 WhatsApp, a high level of trust in informal channels of media, and distrus=
t in institutions thanks to years of neglect by successive governments.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"=
><a href=3D"https://geopoliticalfutures.com/mailster/401981/5e27030c0318f09=
6cd26f3e94fdcf2a7/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW9wb2xpdGljYWxmdXR1cmVzLmNvbS93cC1jb250ZW50L=
3VwbG9hZHMvMjAyNS8wNS9BZnJpY2FfRGlzaW5mb3JtYXRpb24uanBn" style=3D"color:#0e=
6ba5;text-decoration:none;padding:2px 0px"><img class=3D"aligncenter size-f=
ull wp-image-401960" src=3D"https://geopoliticalfutures.com/wp-content/uplo=
ads/2025/05/Africa_Disinformation.jpg" alt=3D"Disinformation Campaigns in A=
frica" width=3D"600" style=3D"outline:none;text-decoration:none;-ms-interpo=
lation-mode:bicubic;display:block;max-width:100%;height:auto;border:none"><=
/a><br>
<em><a href=3D"https://geopoliticalfutures.com/mailster/401981/5e27030c0318=
f096cd26f3e94fdcf2a7/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW9wb2xpdGljYWxmdXR1cmVzLmNvbS93cC1jb250ZW=
50L3VwbG9hZHMvMjAyNS8wNS9BZnJpY2FfRGlzaW5mb3JtYXRpb24uanBn/1" style=3D"colo=
r:#0e6ba5;text-decoration:none;padding:2px 0px">(click to enlarge)</a></em>=
</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Recent events in R=
omania are similarly illustrative. The presidential election last year feat=
ured a relative unknown outsider named Calin Georgescu, who rose to promine=
nce and topped the polls in a major surprise to observers and established p=
arties alike. The constitutional court annulled the election results after =
intelligence documents revealed a targeted Russian influence operation was =
promoting Georgescu. And it just so happened that he favored closer relatio=
ns with Moscow than with Brussels.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Here again, Russia=
 was able to effectively leverage an existing discontent with the status qu=
o to promote an outsider who could have fundamentally altered Romania's dem=
ocratic outlook. The campaign was conducted via readily available media cha=
nnels such as Instagram, TikTok and WhatsApp. In other words, Moscow was al=
most able to fundamentally change the direction of Romania=E2=80=99s foreig=
n policy using a relatively paltry amount of resources.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">This case was the =
first time a Western country was forced to take concrete and drastic steps =
to counter FIMI operations. But in a democratic country, this has consequen=
ces of its own. The people who voted for Georgescu believe democracy was un=
dermined by the court=E2=80=99s nullification of the election results, whil=
e the people who voted against him also believed they were undermined. Gove=
rnments that follow the example of Bucharest risk pushing more people to ex=
treme parties, especially if they believe mainstream parties are working ag=
ainst them. (It=E2=80=99s important to note, too, that no one likes to admi=
t that they were duped. This entrenchment adds another layer of complexity =
to an already difficult problem.)</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>New Risks<=
/strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Over the past two =
years, the risk posed by FIMI has been made worse by generative AI and auto=
mation. Generative AI allows users to produce images and videos that are ne=
arly indistinguishable from reality. Large language models allow external a=
ctors to produce convincing content in many languages without needing to ex=
pend the time and resources to groom local assets or learn the language oth=
erwise. Similarly, automation is a vital tool for amplifying messages hundr=
eds of times to =E2=80=9Cflood the zone=E2=80=9D with information. Whereas =
before troll farms required thousands of employees to produce fake or docto=
red content, they can now be mass-produced and distributed with minimal lab=
or across multiple platforms.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">FIMI is a risk tha=
t evolves in lockstep with new technologies. That one country can affect an=
other=E2=80=99s elections for its own geostrategic ends is fundamentally an=
 act of aggression and undermines the entire democratic process. The soluti=
ons required are complex and long-term. Russian Chief of General Staff&nbsp=
;Gen. Valery Gerasimov has said that the world is moving to a =E2=80=9Cnonl=
inear battlefield,=E2=80=9D where psychological, informational and cognitiv=
e operations are just as decisive to outcomes as kinetic operations. Vulner=
able groups are manipulated for a host of reasons, and the cost of doing so=
 is significantly lower than a conventional challenge to the status quo.</p=
>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">On a state level, =
the European Union is a leader in countering FIMI. These operations require=
 more than just fact-checking; once the disinformation is out there, the da=
mage is often already done. Effective counteroperations require investment =
in media literacy, regulatory frameworks for tech platforms to prevent rapi=
d dissemination, and coordinated intelligence sharing among allies who unde=
rstand the risks.</p>

